<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[264,1325,732,1558]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,432,972,998]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Thorax (except scutellum) black in ground colour; posterior half or more of the scutellum reddish or yellow. Abdomen black (except for reddish spots on sides of tergites 
<number box="[359,374,1052,1078]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="3.0">3</number>
and rarely 
<number box="[512,528,1052,1078]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="4.0">4</number>
) without blue reflections, densely and evenly covered with silvergrey microtrichosity (
<figureCitation box="[515,600,1092,1118]" captionStart="FIGURES 27 – 30" captionStartId="23.[264,370,1702,1723]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,315,1675]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[264,1323,315,1676]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 27 – 30. Abdomen of Pales spp. in dorsal view. 27. Pales latifrons Kugler Ψ (Israel). 28. Pales murina Mesnil ♂ (Iran). 29. Pales cyanea (Macquart) ♂ (Spain, Canary Isalands). 30. Pales marae sp. nov. paratype ♂ (Italy, Sardinia, Cagliari prov.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170913/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<number box="[567,600,1092,1118]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="28.0">28</number>
</figureCitation>
). Tibiae yellow or brownish­yellow, but black on the basal 
<number box="[1286,1301,1092,1118]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[1308,1323,1092,1118]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="3.0">3</number>
– 
<number box="[277,292,1132,1158]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[300,315,1132,1158]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="2.0">2</number>
of their ventral side. ɗ: postpedicel 
<number box="[762,798,1132,1158]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="3.7">3.7</number>
–4.0 times as long as the pedicel; height of facial ridge 
<number box="[407,522,1172,1198]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1.045" valueMax="1.15" valueMin="0.94">0.94–1.15</number>
times as long as the frons in lateral view; frons 
<number box="[1100,1217,1172,1198]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="0.755" valueMax="0.78" valueMin="0.73">0.73–0.78</number>
times as wide as an eye in dorsal view; fore claws longer than tarsomere 
<number box="[1044,1061,1212,1238]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="5.0">5</number>
; abdominal tergites 
<number box="[1305,1320,1212,1238]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="3.0">3</number>
and 
<number box="[313,328,1252,1278]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="4.0">4</number>
without median discal setae (rarely 
<number box="[751,765,1252,1278]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="2.0">2</number>
short and weak on tergite 
<number box="[1075,1092,1252,1278]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="4.0">4</number>
); terminalia in posterior view as in 
<figureCitation box="[478,569,1292,1318]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 26" captionStartId="22.[264,370,1728,1749]" captionTargetBox="[300,1254,322,1700]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[267,1295,315,1716]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 26. Male terminalia, scale bar 0.5 mm. 20 – 23. Pales pavida (Meigen). 20. (Italy, Latium), cerci and surstyli in posterior view. 21. Cerci and right surstylus in right lateral view (Germany, Baden­Württemberg). 22. (Germany, Baden­Württemberg), cerci and surstyli in posterior view. 23. (Italy, Latium), epandrial complex in lateral view. 24 – 25. Pales processioneae (Ratzeburg) (Germany, Baden­Württemberg). 24. Cerci and surstyli in posterior view. 25. Epandrial complex in right lateral view. 26. Pales latifrons Kugler (Israel), cerci and surstyli in posterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170912/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<number box="[536,569,1292,1318]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="24.0">24</number>
</figureCitation>
. Female differs from male as follows: frons wider, 
<number box="[1206,1258,1292,1318]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="0.9">0.90</number>
–1.00 times as wide as an eye in dorsal view. Postpedicel about 
<number box="[979,1067,1332,1358]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="2.8" valueMax="3.1" valueMin="2.5">2.5–3.1</number>
times as long as the pedicel.
</paragraph>
